00:30:24.570 --> 00:30:26.710
Do you create conditions
that make it happen?

00:30:26.710 --> 00:30:27.586
Or what would you do?

00:30:27.586 --> 00:30:29.751
GORDON CHAMBERS: I have a
different writing process.

00:30:29.751 --> 00:30:30.890
It just depends what it is.

00:30:30.890 --> 00:30:33.300
Some songs of mine I
write at the piano,

00:30:33.300 --> 00:30:34.790
and they tend to
be more ballads.

00:30:34.790 --> 00:30:36.730
But a lot of times,
collaborations

00:30:36.730 --> 00:30:39.630
are about opposites attracting.

00:30:39.630 --> 00:30:42.990
So a lot of my songs
have been written

00:30:42.990 --> 00:30:46.000
with producers that were
quote unquote "beat guys."

00:30:46.000 --> 00:30:49.460
But the producers I got
a chance to work with

00:30:49.460 --> 00:30:50.910
were more than just beat people.

00:30:50.910 --> 00:30:52.730
Stevie J. And Dave
Hall, these were

00:30:52.730 --> 00:30:56.160
guys who had real fabulous
musicianship on top

00:30:56.160 --> 00:30:56.820
of their beats.

00:30:56.820 --> 00:30:57.960
But they had hard beats.

00:30:57.960 --> 00:31:01.470
They knew how to knock
their heads in the studio.

00:31:01.470 --> 00:31:03.384
My glasses are falling off.

00:31:03.384 --> 00:31:04.800
It was like, I was
a man who would

00:31:04.800 --> 00:31:06.350
come in with the
melody on top, and they

00:31:06.350 --> 00:31:07.558
would have the beat knocking.

00:31:07.558 --> 00:31:10.111
And that's how you had that
great opposites attract

00:31:10.111 --> 00:31:10.610
of music.

00:31:10.610 --> 00:31:14.490
So sometimes it was a situation
of being given a great track.

00:31:14.490 --> 00:31:17.240
"If You Love Me" was a track
that Dave Hall presented me.

00:31:17.240 --> 00:31:18.480
And he gave it to me on a CD.

00:31:18.480 --> 00:31:20.220
And one morning-- I'm
Jamaican, so Jamaicans

00:31:20.220 --> 00:31:21.150
are notoriously late.

00:31:21.150 --> 00:31:23.140
I was on time today, though.

00:31:23.140 --> 00:31:24.760
Jamaicans are notoriously late.

00:31:24.760 --> 00:31:26.690
So one day, I was
on my way, late

00:31:26.690 --> 00:31:28.706
to my job at "Essence"
magazine, I swear to God.

00:31:28.706 --> 00:31:31.080
It just started to pour rain
as I was thinking about what

00:31:31.080 --> 00:31:33.219
lie I could call Susan
Taylor with and tell her

00:31:33.219 --> 00:31:35.760
I was going to be late, because
I had every lie in the book--

00:31:35.760 --> 00:31:38.710
the cat, the grandmother died,
the this, the that, blah, blah.

00:31:38.710 --> 00:31:39.850
What lie can I tell?

00:31:39.850 --> 00:31:42.020
I swear, God was like,
don't tell any more lies,

00:31:42.020 --> 00:31:43.670
because the rain
started pouring down.

00:31:43.670 --> 00:31:47.460
I popped Dave Hall's track
into the CD player of my car,

00:31:47.460 --> 00:31:49.270
and all I heard
were those chords.

00:31:49.270 --> 00:31:51.840
And the first line of "If
You Love Me" came to me.

00:31:51.840 --> 00:31:54.750
"I don't want to rain on this
parade," inspired by the rain

00:31:54.750 --> 00:31:56.261
as I was late to work.

00:31:56.261 --> 00:31:57.260
Songs can come anywhere.

00:31:57.260 --> 00:31:59.365
I've literally had songs hit me.

00:31:59.365 --> 00:32:00.740
One day, I was
getting a haircut.

00:32:00.740 --> 00:32:01.970
I was in the barber shop.

00:32:01.970 --> 00:32:03.880
And this idea came to me.

00:32:03.880 --> 00:32:05.770
And the barber
scratched my head,

00:32:05.770 --> 00:32:08.054
because I was like, I
need a pen, I need a pen.

00:32:08.054 --> 00:32:09.720
And he's like, yo,
I'm about to cut you.

00:32:09.720 --> 00:32:12.540
And he really did cut me
with the barber thing.

00:32:12.540 --> 00:32:17.630
But that was when the words to
a song that I wrote for Brandy

00:32:17.630 --> 00:32:20.500
called "One Voice," they
came to me immediately.

00:32:20.500 --> 00:32:23.580
So I think being a songwriter
is about being open,

00:32:23.580 --> 00:32:26.364
having something to say.

00:32:26.364 --> 00:32:27.780
It takes being a
sensitive person.

00:32:27.780 --> 00:32:30.240
You have to be in touch
with your emotions.

00:32:30.240 --> 00:32:33.562
You can't be the alpha male
to be a great songwriter.

00:32:33.562 --> 00:32:35.270
You really have to be
the sensitive male.

00:32:35.270 --> 00:32:38.570
You have to know what you feel
and be able to articulate it,

00:32:38.570 --> 00:32:42.430
because the women audience,
they get it right away.

00:32:42.430 --> 00:32:45.050
But it's interesting, since I've
become a performer, not just

00:32:45.050 --> 00:32:47.640
a songwriter, I have found
that my songs now, especially

00:32:47.640 --> 00:32:49.350
the songs on my solo
albums, are speaking

00:32:49.350 --> 00:32:50.829
to the men very poignantly.

00:32:50.829 --> 00:32:52.870
A lot of the men have told
me that buy my records

00:32:52.870 --> 00:32:54.661
and go to my concerts,
they said, thank you

00:32:54.661 --> 00:32:58.270
for saying for me what I didn't
have the emotional sensitivity

00:32:58.270 --> 00:33:00.120
and that kind of courage to say.

00:33:00.120 --> 00:33:01.632
So it's about being open.

00:33:01.632 --> 00:33:02.840
RYAN LOREN: Thanks very much.

00:33:02.840 --> 00:33:04.689
So can you talk
about, obviously,

00:33:04.689 --> 00:33:05.730
you're not just a writer.

00:33:05.730 --> 00:33:08.150
You're also a performer,
singer, artist.

00:33:08.150 --> 00:33:10.870
So what was the
critical point where

00:33:10.870 --> 00:33:13.927
you decided, all right,
I'm going to do this?

00:33:13.927 --> 00:33:16.260
GORDON CHAMBERS: It had been
in my mind for a long time.

00:33:16.260 --> 00:33:18.060
Because I was in the
studio all the time

00:33:18.060 --> 00:33:20.135
writing songs for
other artists, people

00:33:20.135 --> 00:33:22.260
don't realize that I sang
all of those songs first.

00:33:22.260 --> 00:33:23.720
I did the demos
for "I Apologize."

00:33:23.720 --> 00:33:24.810
I did the demo
for "Missing You."

00:33:24.810 --> 00:33:26.310
I did the demo for
"If You Love Me."

00:33:26.310 --> 00:33:27.730
So the artist who
record the songs

00:33:27.730 --> 00:33:29.146
were always listening
to my voice.

00:33:29.146 --> 00:33:31.630
I would lay the lead vocals
and the background vocals.

00:33:31.630 --> 00:33:33.629
I was always in the
studios recording.

00:33:33.629 --> 00:33:34.670
And I knew how to record.

00:33:34.670 --> 00:33:36.503
And then in my years
as entertainment editor

00:33:36.503 --> 00:33:38.630
at "Essence," I was going
to all the concerts.

00:33:38.630 --> 00:33:40.350
I've seen everyone in concert.

00:33:40.350 --> 00:33:42.934
And I was going backstage, I was
hanging out with the artists,

00:33:42.934 --> 00:33:43.975
interviewing the artists.

00:33:43.975 --> 00:33:45.830
So I was having the
best artist development

00:33:45.830 --> 00:33:48.020
that one could ever have,
because I was seeing it

00:33:48.020 --> 00:33:50.080
on the side of a journalist.

00:33:50.080 --> 00:33:52.134
So I was really learning
about the business.

00:33:52.134 --> 00:33:53.300
But then there was the fear.

00:33:53.300 --> 00:33:56.080
I was like, afraid to step
from one side to the other.

00:33:56.080 --> 00:33:58.750
And it was something I wanted to
do, but I was afraid to do it.

00:33:58.750 --> 00:34:00.610
And then sometimes you
just have to be open

00:34:00.610 --> 00:34:02.880
and ask people for help.

00:34:02.880 --> 00:34:05.772
What happened was
I started to-- not

00:34:05.772 --> 00:34:07.480
get afraid of making
the music but afraid

00:34:07.480 --> 00:34:09.816
of asking the very people
around me to help me,

00:34:09.816 --> 00:34:12.190
because I knew that I didn't
have tons and tons of money.

00:34:12.190 --> 00:34:15.424
But I want to make
a quality project.

00:34:15.424 --> 00:34:17.840
But the day that changed my
life was, I was in the studio,

00:34:17.840 --> 00:34:21.290
producing the late and
great Whitney Houston.

00:34:21.290 --> 00:34:22.749
And I was producing
a song for her.

00:34:22.749 --> 00:34:25.039
And I told her that I wanted
her to hit a certain note.

00:34:25.039 --> 00:34:27.219
And I kept telling her to
hit it higher and higher.

00:34:27.219 --> 00:34:28.677
And then she looked
me in the face,

00:34:28.677 --> 00:34:30.949
and she said, "I think
you want to do what I do.

00:34:30.949 --> 00:34:32.365
And if that's what
you want to do,

00:34:32.365 --> 00:34:35.530
then that's what
you need to do."

00:34:35.530 --> 00:34:37.449
And I looked at her,
like, what did she say?

00:34:37.449 --> 00:34:38.892
She was really in my face, too.

00:34:38.892 --> 00:34:41.100
And she's from Newark, so
what she gets in your face,

00:34:41.100 --> 00:34:41.940
it's kind of.

00:34:41.940 --> 00:34:46.162
So the Newark came on,
the Brooklyn stepped back.

00:34:46.162 --> 00:34:47.620
And I said, well,
what do you mean?

00:34:47.620 --> 00:34:48.920
She said, I think
you want to sing.

00:34:48.920 --> 00:34:50.150
If that's what you
want to do, then that's

00:34:50.150 --> 00:34:51.670
what you should be doing.

00:34:51.670 --> 00:34:56.000
And it was like one those
times when an angel speaks Word

00:34:56.000 --> 00:34:57.400
into your life, and you feel it.

00:34:57.400 --> 00:34:58.860
And it penetrates your heart.

00:34:58.860 --> 00:35:02.230
So shortly after that, I went
to church the Sunday after that,

00:35:02.230 --> 00:35:06.380
and my minister Pastor Trouffant
at Emmanuel Baptist Church

00:35:06.380 --> 00:35:10.562
in Brooklyn gave a sermon
about how not to wait,

00:35:10.562 --> 00:35:12.520
that now is your time,
whatever you want to do.

00:35:12.520 --> 00:35:15.360
And he talked about
how Jesus died at 36.

00:35:15.360 --> 00:35:17.390
And many of the miracles
that you read about

00:35:17.390 --> 00:35:19.600
were done in the last
three years of his life.

00:35:19.600 --> 00:35:21.690
So he said, don't
wait for your time

00:35:21.690 --> 00:35:23.190
if there's something
you want to do.

00:35:23.190 --> 00:35:26.090
And so after Whitney
preached to me in the studio

00:35:26.090 --> 00:35:29.100
and then Pastor Trouffant
preached to me, then I said,

00:35:29.100 --> 00:35:29.946
it's time.

00:35:29.946 --> 00:35:31.070
The universe is telling me.

00:35:31.070 --> 00:35:33.134
And I called all my
friends in the business.

00:35:33.134 --> 00:35:35.300
And I said, I think I'm
ready to make a solo record.

00:35:35.300 --> 00:35:36.970
And everyone said yes.

00:35:36.970 --> 00:35:39.250
My producer Troy Taylor
said, come on through.

00:35:39.250 --> 00:35:40.760
We're going to do
it in my basement.

00:35:40.760 --> 00:35:44.110
And we went to his basement, my
friend's publicist, Gwendolyn

00:35:44.110 --> 00:35:44.790
Quinn.

00:35:44.790 --> 00:35:46.956
These are people I had all
worked with at "Essence,"

00:35:46.956 --> 00:35:49.480
but I was afraid to ask them
to help me on my own stuff.

00:35:49.480 --> 00:35:51.870
Gwendolyn Quinn said,
I'll do your PR.

00:35:51.870 --> 00:35:53.510
Everyone I reached
out to said, we

00:35:53.510 --> 00:35:55.100
have been waiting
for this moment.

00:35:55.100 --> 00:35:57.280
And they all helped me,
started booking shows,

00:35:57.280 --> 00:35:59.021
booked the very first
show at Joe's Pub.

00:35:59.021 --> 00:36:01.020
I swear, I thought 10
people were going to come.

00:36:01.020 --> 00:36:03.230
They had to turn
200 people away.

00:36:03.230 --> 00:36:04.730
Then the night of
the album release,

00:36:04.730 --> 00:36:07.150
we had the album release
around the corner at BB

00:36:07.150 --> 00:36:09.690
King's-- packed, packed,
almost a sold out show.

00:36:09.690 --> 00:36:12.210
It's just from the jump,
it's as if the world

00:36:12.210 --> 00:36:14.444
had been waiting for me
to step into my greatness.

00:36:14.444 --> 00:36:15.860
And sometimes
that's what you have

00:36:15.860 --> 00:36:18.026
to do is, just listen to
what the universe is trying

00:36:18.026 --> 00:36:20.090
to tell you and don't be
afraid to step into it.

00:36:20.090 --> 00:36:21.750
RYAN LOREN: Thanks a lot.

00:36:21.750 --> 00:36:23.276
Let's give it up for that.

00:36:23.276 --> 00:36:25.490
[APPLAUSE]

00:36:25.490 --> 00:36:29.080
RYAN LOREN: Last question--
so about the music, talk to us

00:36:29.080 --> 00:36:31.090
about what the last
album meant to you.

00:36:31.090 --> 00:36:33.090
That was your third
album, "Sincere,"

00:36:33.090 --> 00:36:35.070
and then what's next?

00:36:35.070 --> 00:36:37.720
GORDON CHAMBERS: Every album
gets more and more personal.

00:36:37.720 --> 00:36:40.095
The first album was called
"Introducing Gordon Chambers,"

00:36:40.095 --> 00:36:42.680
which featured collaborations
with friends-- Roy

00:36:42.680 --> 00:36:44.085
Hargrove, Mike Phillips.

00:36:46.740 --> 00:36:48.370
Carl Thomas is on that album.

00:36:48.370 --> 00:36:52.630
So the first album had a
slightly jazzy feeling to it.

00:36:52.630 --> 00:36:55.550
"Love Stories" featured
a duet with Ledisi,

00:36:55.550 --> 00:36:57.920
"To Love Again,"
which became a big hit

00:36:57.920 --> 00:37:00.060
record on a lot
of radio stations.

00:37:00.060 --> 00:37:02.830
Then the third album, "Sincere,"
which is the most recent album,

00:37:02.830 --> 00:37:04.579
I just wanted to make
an album that I felt

00:37:04.579 --> 00:37:05.609
was very, very personal.

00:37:05.609 --> 00:37:07.150
And I want to make
an album this time

00:37:07.150 --> 00:37:10.270
from the perspective of
being a live performer.

00:37:10.270 --> 00:37:12.700
The first two albums were
more from the perspective

00:37:12.700 --> 00:37:16.400
of a songwriter that's
writing and also sings.

00:37:16.400 --> 00:37:19.830
This one was started from the
perspective of a performer,

00:37:19.830 --> 00:37:23.882
and I wanted to give people
lyrically a backstage, up close

00:37:23.882 --> 00:37:25.840
and personal emotional
look at what my life is.

00:37:25.840 --> 00:37:27.290
I wanted to be
more as vulnerable

00:37:27.290 --> 00:37:29.467
as I could be with the lyrics.

00:37:29.467 --> 00:37:31.050
That's why the first
song on the album

00:37:31.050 --> 00:37:32.674
is called "I'm In
The Band," because it

00:37:32.674 --> 00:37:35.109
was written from
that perspective.

00:37:35.109 --> 00:37:37.150
I'm in the process of
making another album called

00:37:37.150 --> 00:37:39.530
"Conversations With God."

00:37:39.530 --> 00:37:42.500
And it's going to be
an inspirational album.

00:37:42.500 --> 00:37:44.802
It's going to have a
spiritual tonality,

00:37:44.802 --> 00:37:46.510
but I'm also talking
about relationships,

00:37:46.510 --> 00:37:47.510
I'm talking about life.

00:37:47.510 --> 00:37:48.926
And I'm just getting
more and more

00:37:48.926 --> 00:37:51.250
vulnerable with each album.

00:37:51.250 --> 00:37:54.450
I feel that the
R&amp;B male tradition

00:37:54.450 --> 00:37:57.750
has been taken over
by the sexuality.

00:37:57.750 --> 00:38:00.510
And I want to provide
more of the sensitivity

00:38:00.510 --> 00:38:04.189
and the sensuality into
the lyrical landscape.

00:38:04.189 --> 00:38:05.230
RYAN LOREN: Amen to that.

00:38:09.770 --> 00:38:10.740
Thanks for being here.

00:38:10.740 --> 00:38:14.490
Everybody, I've learned a
lot from Gordon in my life.

00:38:14.490 --> 00:38:16.182
We've known each
other a few years.

00:38:16.182 --> 00:38:17.640
You're a role model
to many people.

00:38:17.640 --> 00:38:17.990
GORDON CHAMBERS: Thank you.

00:38:17.990 --> 00:38:19.630
RYAN LOREN: Thanks so
much for being here.

00:38:19.630 --> 00:38:21.880
GORDON CHAMBERS: Thank you
for doing this for us here.

00:38:21.880 --> 00:38:22.370
Thank you.

00:38:22.370 --> 00:38:23.286
RYAN LOREN: Of course.

00:38:23.286 --> 00:38:24.625
Thank you.

00:38:24.625 --> 00:38:26.000
GORDON CHAMBERS:
See y'all later.

00:38:26.000 --> 00:38:29.850
[APPLAUSE]

